   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1826-05_page02.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <salute>
                  <persName>My dear <hi rend="underline">Cousin</hi>
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>Now that you are <hi rend="underline">a great man at the head</hi>
               <lb/>
               of the <hi rend="underline">Paving Board</hi> of <hi rend="underline">all</hi>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> you may<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">guess</hi> without even being a born American<lb/>
               that every one who can will claim cousin<lb/>
               ship with you - Whether all will have their<lb/>
               <add>claim</add> allowed or have as good a right to claim<lb/>
               kindred I leave to your Honorable self as<lb/>
               the head of the <choice>
                  <orig>Hon<hi rend="superscript">ble</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>Honorable</reg>
               </choice> paving board to <choice>
                  <orig>deter<lb/>
               mine</orig>
                  <reg>determine</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>My present suit is in favour of a youth<lb/>
               who is neither kith nor kin to me, and whom<lb/>
               I have never seen and of whom I know<lb/>
               nought excepting that he is nephew to a man<lb/>
               of whom I know a great deal of good -<lb/>
               viz <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KellJ1">James Kelly</persName> of <unclear>Gourte</unclear> &amp; Kilcoursey - one of<lb/>
               <!--Unsure if Kilcoursey refers to a family barony name or actual location-->
               our very best tenants - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KellJ1">James Kelly</persName> entreats<lb/>
               me to write to you in favor of a nephew of his<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JackR1">Mr. Richard Jackson</persName> - one of the Jacksons of<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Killogue_IE">Killogue</placeName> - This young man had a small <choice>
                  <orig>pro<lb/>
               perty</orig>
                  <reg>property</reg>
               </choice> but his affairs having become embarrassed<lb/>
               (as affairs somehow or other are apt to do) he<lb/>
               wishes - very naturally, to get into some good<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1826-05_page02.jpg"/>
               little snug place or situation by which he<lb/>
               could live; and he has a notion that in the<lb/>
               paving board you could just <unclear>shuste</unclear> him -<lb/>
               I have represented to my friend <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KellJ1">James Kelly</persName>
               <lb/>
               that I really cannot write a letter of <choice>
                  <orig>
                     <hi rend="underline">recommen<lb/>
               dation</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>recommendation</reg>
               </choice> for a man of whose qualifications &amp; <choice>
                  <orig>cha<lb/>
               racter</orig>
                  <reg>character</reg>
               </choice> I know nothing - But that I am ready<lb/>
               to give his nephew an introduction to you<lb/>
               and <del>that</del> I advise <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KellJ1">Kelly</persName> to go up to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName>
               <lb/>
               &amp; vouch for his nephew himself to you -<lb/>
               This he will do - and would set out to do this<lb/>
               day but that a fair at which he must buy or<lb/>
               sell comes in the way, and he could not set<lb/>
               out for a day or two without great loss - <choice>
                  <orig>Mean<lb/>
               time</orig>
                  <reg>Meantime</reg>
               </choice> he wishes that you would be so kind<lb/>
               to let his nephew see you that you may judge<lb/>
               by examining him externally &amp; internally <choice>
                  <orig>whe<lb/>
               =ther</orig>
                  <reg>whether</reg>
               </choice> he is fit for any situation in which you<lb/>
               could employ him - The young man is now<lb/>
               in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName> &amp; every day at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WebbX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Webbs</persName> office where<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KellJ1">Kelly</persName> thinks all the world must have business<lb/>
               or may be likely to resort - By my counsel <choice>
                  <orig>how-<lb/>
                  ever</orig>
                  <reg>however</reg>
               </choice>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KellJ1">Kelly</persName> writes to his nephew <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JackR1">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Rich<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
                     </orig>
                     <reg>Richard</reg>
                  </choice> Jackson</persName> desir<lb/>
               <!--How do we do a choice tag for a word that goes across two pages?-->
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1826-05_page04.jpg"/>
               ing him to call on <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeX1">Major Edgeworth</persName> at the Paving<lb/>
               Board -</p>
            <lb/>
            <p>Do what your conscience will allow you<lb/>
               to do for him to oblige<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               Your affectionate cousin<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KellJ1">Kelly</persName> will be in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Town</placeName>
                  <note type="certainty">It is reasonable to believe that "Town" here is referring to Edgeworthstown.</note> in a few days &amp; will<lb/>
                  wait upon you with his nephew in case<lb/>
                  the youth should not have the courage to present<lb/>
                  himself without an introduction. But he is<lb/>
                  not a true-born Irishman if courage fails him<lb/>
                  - so far - Pray do not give away all the<lb/>
                  <unclear>multitude</unclear> of places which, (as <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KellJ1">Kelly</persName>
                  <unclear>conceives</unclear>
                  <lb/>
                  you have to give before he can reach <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName>
                  <lb/>
                  &amp; make his own representations for his nephew<lb/>
                  - the most weighty of which is that he would<lb/>
                  go security for him. I believe -<lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
            <closer>
               <address>
                  <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1826-05_page01.jpg"/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeX1">Major Edgeworth</persName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>Paving = Board</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
               </address>
            </closer>
